The easiest way to do this is with the text processor:  <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://docs.textadventures.co.uk/quest/text_processor.html">http://docs.textadventures.co.uk/quest/ ... essor.html</a><!-- m -->

When outputting text, you can specify object attributes inline in the text. For example, you can output this string:

[code:1tedo6jf]{player&#46;title}, there are labour day riots from {player&#46;CityA} to {player&#46;CityB}&#46;[/code:1tedo6jf]
The bits inside the {}'s in this case refer to attributes on the player, which you can set up with (for example):

player.title = &quot;Chancellor&quot;
player.CityA = &quot;Hamburg&quot;
player.CityB = &quot;Stuttgart&quot;

You can actually store the attributes on any available object (another reasonable on e would be the &quot;game&quot; object), but the player at least makes some sense in this case. <!-- s:) --><img src="{SMILIES_PATH}/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><!-- s:) -->

You can use scripting commands to set attributes on an object in response to what the user selects (use a page type that has scripting).

